results.name: Let S(n) denote the sequence formed by concatenating the decimal numbers 1,2,3,..., omitting n; a(n) is the smallest prime in S(n), or -1 if no term in S(n) is prime.
comment: A262300 is now the main entry for this question.
example: a(8) = 1234567910111213...1873 (ending at 1873, a 6384-digit probable prime, and too large to display here) was found by _David Broadhurst_ on Sep 27 2015.
Sep 28, 2015: _David Broadhurst_ has also found a(10), a(12), a(14), a(16), a(17), a(18), and a(20). See A262300 for their values.
xref: A262300 gives the last term in S(n) when a prime appears for the first time.
See A262571-A262582 for the sequences S(1) through S(12).
Cf. A007908 (which plays the role of S(0)).
For the primes in S(1) and S(2) see A089987, A262298.
results.author: _N. J. A. Sloane_ and Jerrold B. Tunnell, Sep 25 2015
